Question:
Concatenate the first two words that have even lengths from a list.
Input:
List<String> words = Arrays.asList("apple", "banana", "cherry", "date");

Solution:
Java 8 Streams concatenate first two even-length words using filter, limit(2), and joining(" "). For input ["apple", "banana", "cherry", "date"] (lengths 5,6,6,4), "banana cherry".

#Step-by-Step Logic
Stream words via stream(). Filter even lengths: filter(word -> word.length() % 2 == 0). Limit to 2: limit(2). Collect joined: collect(joining(" ")).

#Complete Implementation

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

public class ConcatEvenLengthWords {
    public static String concatFirstTwoEven(List<String> words) {
        return words.stream()
                    .filter(word -> word.length() % 2 == 0)
                    .limit(2)
                    .collect(Collectors.joining(" "));
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> words = Arrays.asList("apple", "banana", "cherry", "date");
        String result = concatFirstTwoEven(words);
        System.out.println(result);  // banana cherry
    }
}

Prints banana cherry. Short-circuits after 2 matches.

#Thought Process
Filter selects even-length (6,6,4 → banana,cherry,date). limit(2) takes first two. joining(" ") efficient concat. Handles <2 gracefully (empty or single).

#Edge Cases Analysis
<2 even-length: Empty string if 0, single word if 1.
Empty list: Empty string.
Null list: NPE.
Null words: null.length() NPE; filter nulls.
Empty strings: Length 0 even → included.
All odd: Empty.
